Learn me about Uncertainty.
15 posts
river-wind
Ars Praefectus
et Subscriptor
Registered: Nov 20, 2001Posts: 5547
Posted: Thu Sep 20, 2007 10:17 am
I've been fighting with this since Middle School. What and Why is the uncertainty principal in quantum physics?http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Uncertainty_principleFrom what I've gathered over the years, it is due to the difficulties in combining the math for particles with the math for waves - one must either look at the item of study as a wave, or collapse the wave-form in order to treat the object as a particle; limiting the scope of the equation to the strongest signal area (the 'standing wave') at the expense of all the outlying points otherwise covered by the wave function.Wave-particles are not waves or particles, but can exhibit the properties of each depending on the situation at hand. The equations we have to predict the behavior of each (as verified in lab experiments) are extremely good at what they do.But neither set works to completely predict a wave-particle at all times, and the problem is compounded by the fact that figuring out the data for one set makes us less uncertain about the other, due to the localization property of Fourier transforms."the more concentrated f(t) is, the more spread out F(w) is. In particular, if we "squeeze" a function in t, it spreads out in w and vise-versa; and we cannot arbitrarily concentrate both the function and its Fourier transform."http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fourier_transform#Localization_propertySo what this means is (in high school physics terms) that we can know only two of the three at any given time: position, direction, and velocity. What this also means is that the more accurately you measure the two known items, the less accurate any information about the third will be.I understand all that on a book-learnin' level, but it all feels like wood to me, instead of marble (in Einstein's terminology). It doesn't feel smooth. Since wave-particles are not waves nor particles, why do we limit ourselves to wave math and particle math, and the uncertainty that exists between the two? Might there be an as-of-yet undiscovered math that describes wave-particle behavior perfectly? And if some new Newton were to come along and invent that math as Newton invented calculus, would the localization property no longer apply, and would the Heisenberg Uncertainty principal fall by the wayside?Or am I missing something key about the whole concept, and Heisenberg's principal is not one rooted in math, but in nature itself? Is the principal actually suggesting that until a particle is "measured" by interaction with something else, that its waveform is not determined? That prior to a particle striking a photo sheet, no 'particle' even really exists?NOTE: I am not the bestest at math, which may very well be where my problem lies. any explanations that tend toward English will be more understandable - the more formulas, the more lost I will become - I have no degree in physics, and thus much of the basic formula functions are not in my vocabulary. Pop-sci books, Feynman's Lectures and books, and wikipedia are my level of Physics knowledge. Thanks!
