I'm not really sure about this... I recall Wikipedia's article on it to be quite good, but I can see if I can find something better at a later time (at work now).As for Schrodenger's cat, I recall it was originally supposed to illustrate the absurdity of quantum mechanics. There is no way a cat can be both alive and dead. Over the decades it has evolved to illustrate that an object (the cat in this case) DOES (not can, but does) exist in a superposition of states until it is measured, then one single value will be seen (e.g. alive/dead). Of course, this goofiness is keep in the realm of the very small due to Planck's constant being tiny.EDIT: This derivation illustrates that there is nothing inherently special about Heisenberg's uncertainty principle, as ANY two (Hermitian) operators can be shown to follow that relationship due to the Cauchy-Schwartz inequality.
