quote:Originally posted by zeotherm:As for Schrodenger's cat, I recall it was originally supposed to illustrate the absurdity of quantum mechanics. There is no way a cat can be both alive and dead. Over the decades it has evolved to illustrate that an object (the cat in this case) DOES (not can, but does) exist in a superposition of states until it is measured, then one single value will be seen (e.g. alive/dead). Of course, this goofiness is keep in the realm of the very small due to Planck's constant being tiny. A cat is not a quantum object; you can't have a superposition of states with non-quantum objects. At least, that's been my take on it. The myriad of interactions going on within the at any given time makes quantum-level analysis meaningless, I'd think. Though, I could be quite wrong on this.Besides, just try to shove a cat in a box and not get measurements of its existence!
