quote:Originally posted by Feshy:A cat is not a quantum object; you can't have a superposition of states with non-quantum objects. At least, that's been my take on it. Yeah, and as I understand/recall it that was the point of the experiment. My subsequent explanation was a bit murky, as it assumed a quantum cat. As you reach a certain size/number of atoms(or particles, or objects, etc..)/energy level the statistics of QM converge on certainty and classical mechanics takes over (is recovered (?)). (As an aside, this is why Bose-Einstein condensates are interesting, they represent a macroscopic entity that acts as a quantum one)While it is statistically possible for you to go and walk into a solid wall and completely tunnel your way to the other side, the realistic chances of it ever happening are 0. Yes, the true probability is non-zero, but it is so close it becomes one of those "it'll take 10 times the lifetime of the universe for it happen once" events. This was what I was referring to when I said this "goofiness" (referring to the odd effects of the quantum world) disappear in macroscopic objects because h-bar (planck's constant/2 pi) is so small. If it were a larger value, then we would experience quantum effects on larger objects, if it was big enough we'd see these effects on macroscopic objects and then the world would really be screwy. But this is getting too far off topic... EDIT: Apparently I discussed the later in another thread, and got it confused with this one... My bad. I'll leave my comments, but lets try to keep this focused on the OP's questions and not my accidental derailing sckmcck
Ars Tribunus Militum
