Posted: Thu Sep 20, 2007 12:35 pm
quote:Originally posted by river-wind:quote:Originally posted by Fate Amenable to Change:To measure the frequency accurately you will need to measure it over a certain time, which is likely to mean a certain displacement... Well, that's simple enough. Do others agree that this is a worthwhile summation? Not really. This goes back to which interpretation of QM you subscribe to. Fate's description is known as the hidden variable interpretation. Even though we can't measure the position and moment at the same time, the particle still has a well defined position and momentum.Most physicists will agree that this is incorrect. It's not we can't measure with accuracy. It's that the particle itself does not have a well defined momentum or position. The particle itself doesn't know. A free space electron, such as the one coming out of my electron gun, is known as a wave packet. It is actually comprised of a summation of waves of many possible momenta. It's not that we can't measure with 100% accuracy both the position and momentum. Rather, although the electron is still zero size, it is delocalized, and exists in a region of space with certain probability. (this should not be confused with string theory, where particles are of nonzero size.)
norton_I
Ars Praefectus
Registered: Apr 30, 2001Posts: 3397
Posted: Thu Sep 20, 2007 5:56 pm
quote:Originally posted by sckmcck:Not really. This goes back to which interpretation of QM you subscribe to. Fate's description is known as the hidden variable interpretation. Even though we can't measure the position and moment at the same time, the particle still has a well defined position and momentum.Most physicists will agree that this is incorrect. Yes. To elaborate on this a little, a particle can be in a well-defined, or pure state, yet still not have a well defined position and/or momentum.As an optics guy, I always resort to photons to explain things. Photons have a polarization, which is just the direction the electric field oscillates. I can have a vertically polarized photon, which is an exactly known state. If I put it through a vertical polarizer (A device which only lets through vertical polarization), it will go through 100% of the time -- I know the state exactly. If I put it through a horizontal polarizer, it will be blocked 100% of the time. I can also have a horizontally polarized photon, which is likewise well defined, and is transmitted/blocked by the horizontal/vertical polarizer.The trick is, I can also have a diagonally polarized photon. This is yet another pure, completely known state, it is just rotated 45 degrees. I can use a diagonal polarizer, and it goes through, again, 100% of the time. The trick is, now if I measure this photon with a horizontal or vertical polarizer, I will get either answer (blocked or transmitted) with 50% probability.It isn't that I lacked knowledge of how horizontal or vertical my photon was -- it simply was in a state that wasn't well defined as horizontal or vertical. This happens because 'horizontalness' and 'diagonalness' are what we refer to in a technical sense as 'non-commuting observables.' In more plain language, that means that they can't both be well defined for a photon.A small minority of physicists try to hold on to the notion that my diagonally polarized photon 'internally knew' whether it was going to be vertical or horizontal -- a local hidden variable theory. However, these theories have been almost (but perhaps not quote) conclusively disproven by Bell inequality tests.
