quote: So what this means is (in high school physics terms) that we can know only two of the three at any given time: position, direction, and velocity. What this also means is that the more accurately you measure the two known items, the less accurate any information about the third will be. Just a small correction: Direction is a factor of velocity. Velocity = speed x direction. No, you can't multiply the two. They are a vector, intrinsically tied together in physics. There's only two factors related to The Uncertainty Principle (although these two factors affect a bajillion others).quote:Or am I missing something key about the whole concept, and Heisenberg's principal is not one rooted in math, but in nature itself? Is the principal actually suggesting that until a particle is "measured" by interaction with something else, that its waveform is not determined? That prior to a particle striking a photo sheet, no 'particle' even really exists? Your brain is trying to create a distinction between mathematics and reality. In physics, the math is a model of the reality. If we can perform a mathematical function on a model, then we can see what happens if we do the same thing in reality.The difference between the model and the reality is this: We cannot have any concrete information about any period of time in which we did not perform a measurement. Therefore, as far as our mathematical model is concerned, anything could have happened during those times. We cannot make any statements about what happened, therefore the stuff that happened would not exist in a standard, engineering-style mathematical model. This isn't very useful though, so what they do in quantum physics is create a list of everything that could have happened. This allows you (with no small amount of difficulty) to determine all kinds of things about the events that you examined.Unfortunately this means that, when looking at the list of things that could have happened, from a purely scientific viewpoint, you cannot say that any one or all of the possible events happened. The only way to look at it is that they were all potentially happening, so for all intents and purposes, Schrodinger's cat must be treated as being both alive and dead at the same time. You simply don't know until you perform a measurement. i.e. Open the box.Philosophically, this probably isn't how it is in nature. It's just the only way that quantum events can be treated in order to gain any significant results from studying them. Therefore from a scientific viewpoint, anything and everything happens all the time. There may be some kind of Newtonian-style system of rules governing every quantum event that happens, or we may be living in a hodgepodge of random, undecided events, defined entirely by our perception. But it will never be possible to prove this either way. Hence the long list of people who've had their brains fucked by quantum physics. Once you get over these hurdles, and simply realise that you can still glean information from your list of possible events, it gets a lot easier to deal with.That's my understanding, someone with more knowledge is welcome to critique it.
