Posted: Fri Sep 21, 2007 7:14 am
quote:There's only two factors related to The Uncertainty Principle (although these two factors affect a bajillion others). Just to make sure we're perfectly clear here, the uncertainty principle holds for any two observables (like position and momentum) whose operators don't commute. In other words, if the two don't have a common basis of eigenstates, then you'll have an uncertainty relationship.In the real world, measuring one variable collapses the wavefunction into a well-defined state (say momentum). This has the consequence of making any other observable with which momentum does not commute be ill-defined (like position). It drops out quite nicely when you do a Fourier transform from p->x.quote:What this also means is that the more accurately you measure the two known items, the less accurate any information about the third will be. No. Uncertainty is a relation between any two observables whose operators (like P and X) don't commute.I'll try to dig up a more elementary explanation of the uncertainty between p and x using wave packets so you can get an idea of how the math works without having to deal with Fourier transforms/etc.quote:The trick is, I can also have a diagonally polarized photon. This is yet another pure, completely known state, it is just rotated 45 degrees. I can use a diagonal polarizer, and it goes through, again, 100% of the time. The trick is, now if I measure this photon with a horizontal or vertical polarizer, I will get either answer (blocked or transmitted) with 50% probability. This exaplanation, I like it.
